    {
      "id": "7bdedd000f5e5ac7bc49f58c727708bdb2fdfc31",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 13:36:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "e26474ecfcfa24fd5dc871dbd8188fecda053f54",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-06 19:28:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: No score\n\nThis patch makes me a little uneasy now, since from the tarfile's POV the endianness of *.lov is arbitrary.\n\nIt would be good to see that ll_setxattr() properly accepts lov_user_md in both versions, in both byte orders, on files and directories. BTW, I can see that it does not currently.\n\nAn alternative is to have getxattr always return whatever it says on disk and let user space do the correction. The \"honesty\" of this approach appeals to me.\n\nRe Andreas' comment about making the endainness conversion more clear, I would like to see (and have been working on) functions that take a lum/lmm of any version and endian, and just convert it to host/disk endian. This takes the all of the LOV_MAGIC != cpu_to_le32(LOV_MAGIC) type tests out of line and seems a lot cleaner to me.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "8ec4a3b075514357d66de729528793e2a995ea24",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 126,
        "name": "Ned Bass",
        "email": "bass6@llnl.gov",
        "username": "nedbass"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-06 20:59:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI really wish Lustre would have taken the approach Rob Pike advocates to deal with endianness.\n\nhttp://commandcenter.blogspot.com/2012/04/byte-order-fallacy.html\n\nThat is, use a known byte order for over the wire data streams, then run *the same code* regardless of local endianness to extract data from the stream.  Yes, servers would do some unnecessary bit shifting, but we would have cleaner code and fewer bugs.\n\nRegarding swabbing in user space.  I see the appeal, but I would object based on the lack of symmetry with the write path. The library doesn't have to know anything about endianness when it writes the data, so it shouldn't have to convert it back when it reads it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d16c0bbd8f7c4b8dad3590ade8088b74d8a179ee",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-06 21:20:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> That is, use a known byte order for over the wire data streams, then run *the same code* regardless of local endianness to extract data from the stream. Yes, servers would do some unnecessary bit shifting, but we would have cleaner code and fewer bugs.\n\nIndeed that closest to the \"honest\" alternative I proposed. Use LE on disk, on the wire, and at the xattr syscalls.\n\n> Regarding swabbing in user space. I see the appeal, but I would object based on the lack of symmetry with the write path. The library doesn't have to know anything about endianness when it writes the data, so it shouldn't have to convert it back when it reads it.\n\nInteroperability and robustness over symmetry. Before setxattr() please setup lmm in LE, using cpu_to_leNN(). After getxattr() please inspect magic and swab as needed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "9d49399693a8ab2094defd77b01453e8ce1cd7e5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 126,
        "name": "Ned Bass",
        "email": "bass6@llnl.gov",
        "username": "nedbass"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-07 19:09:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n> Before setxattr() please setup lmm in LE, using cpu_to_leNN().  After getxattr() please inspect magic and swab as needed.\n\nThat seems reasonable to me.\n\nI feel like we need to lay out some well defined semantics before proceeding. I see you have begun to explore the issue in LU-3284. It seems like we're trying to support arbitrary byte order at every point in the communication path, and it's become very muddled.  I like the idea of requiring lmm to be LE both in and out of the xattr interfaces (and  ioctl, for that matter).  That would at least address your concerns about tar.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ea342ed2210e518838e1b4c596228a0bac918362",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-15 17:54:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nMarking -1 as Ned said he would refresh the patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "49646f469248d1b04159562c8e18986e0f78b1d8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 126,
        "name": "Ned Bass",
        "email": "bass6@llnl.gov",
        "username": "nedbass"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-15 18:06:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nI _think_ we've reached consensus that the caller of getxattr() is responsible for swabbing the data.  If that's the case then this patch can be abandoned.  When I refresh Ibb78a607a195282aacfa92b0f396565a4e085346 I'll handle the swabbing in liblustreapi.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
